&quot;Also they are not ambitious enough. Assuming constant time arithmetic of the real numbers should get you more (like maybe even the halting problem).&quot;<p>Agreed. They do at least broach the idea though, this is from the companion paper (more theoretical):<p>&quot;We have thus shown that a UMM is Turing-complete,
namely it can simulate any Turing machine (whether deterministic or not). Note, however, that the reverse is not necessarily true. Namely, we have not demonstrated that a UTM can simulate a UMM, or, equivalently, we have not demonstrated that a UMM is Turing-equivalent. It is worth pointing out that, if we could prove that a UMM is not Turing-equivalent, some (Turing) undecidable problems, such as the halting problem [2], may find solution within our UMM paradigm, thus contradicting the Church-Turing hypothesis [2]. Although this is an intriguing–albeit unlikely– possibility, we leave its study for future work.&quot; 
